import{a as e}from"./chunk-XFATBM7I.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A short set of Kubernetes scenario questions, answered first because it's the smallest section in the source question set. These scenarios test whether you can connect what Kubernetes reports (pod status, endpoints, events) to what is actually happening with your application, its networking, and its lifecycle."}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions and Answers",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",variant:"sketch",items:[{question:"A pod keeps restarting but its application logs show nothing. How do you debug it?",answer:"Start with `kubectl describe pod`. It shows the container's state, exit code, recent events, probe results, whether it was OOMKilled (killed for using too much memory), image or config errors, and whether the node itself is under resource pressure.\n\nNext, check logs from the previous, crashed container with `kubectl logs --previous` \u2014 the current one may not have logged anything yet. If the app is crashing before it even starts logging, look at the entrypoint/command, mounted config files and secrets, the security context, and the container runtime's own events."},{question:"A Kubernetes rolling deployment causes intermittent request failures. What configuration do you review?",answer:"Review the entire traffic handoff, not just replica count. Validate that the **readiness probe** reflects real ability to serve and has an appropriate `startupProbe`, initial delay, thresholds, and port/path; a pod must not become ready before caches, migrations, routes, or sidecars are usable. Check RollingUpdate `maxUnavailable` (often 0 for strict availability), `maxSurge`, minimum replicas, capacity headroom, and rollout progress.\n\nOn termination, make readiness fail/drain first, run a `preStop` delay if the ingress/LB needs propagation time, handle `SIGTERM`, enable Spring graceful shutdown, and make `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` longer than maximum request/drain time. Check ingress/gateway keep-alive, connection draining/deregistration delay, service-mesh sidecar shutdown order, long-lived WebSockets, and endpoint propagation.\n\nOld and new versions overlap, so APIs, events, and database migrations must be backward compatible (expand/contract). Review PDB/topology spread, HPA behavior during rollout, resource requests causing pending pods, probe failures, EndpointSlice events, and per-version 5xx traces. Roll back on SLO regression\u2014not merely when Kubernetes marks rollout complete."},{question:"A pod is terminating. What happens to in-flight requests, and how do you shut down cleanly?",answer:"When a pod is deleted, Kubernetes marks it with a deletion timestamp, removes it from the Service's list of endpoints so no new traffic is routed to it, runs the `preStop` hook if one is defined, and then sends the SIGTERM signal.\n\nYour application should respond by failing its readiness check, stopping acceptance of new work, finishing (draining) requests or messages already in progress, and exiting before `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` runs out. If it doesn't exit in time, Kubernetes forcibly kills it with SIGKILL."},{question:"Kubernetes says the service is healthy, but users receive 503 errors. Where do you start?",answer:`Trace the request path step by step: client \u2192 ingress/gateway \u2192 Service \u2192 EndpointSlice (the list of pod IPs behind a Service) \u2192 pod.

Check that the Service's selector and ports actually match the pods, that pods are marked ready in the EndpointSlice, that ingress routes and TLS certificates are correct, that network policies aren't silently blocking traffic, that sidecars are configured correctly, and that upstream timeouts aren't too short.

Key distinction: a liveness probe only proves the process hasn't crashed \u2014 it says nothing about whether the app can serve traffic. Only the readiness probe proves that.`},{question:"One pod consistently receives 80% of traffic while the remaining pods are almost idle. Why?",answer:`First verify that all replicas are actually eligible: inspect Service selectors, readiness, EndpointSlices, zones, ports, and terminating endpoints. Then inspect the balancing unit. Kubernetes Services/ingresses often balance **connections**, not individual HTTP requests; a few long-lived HTTP/2, gRPC, WebSocket, or keep-alive connections can pin most requests to one pod. Session affinity, sticky cookies, consistent hashing on user/header, topology-aware routing, locality preferences, and uneven ingress/gateway endpoint views can produce the same skew.

Also check whether one pod is a leader, partition owner, scheduled-job runner, or serves a hot cached/sharded key\u2014work may be uneven even if request count is not. Compare ingress and per-pod connection/request metrics, EndpointSlices from each gateway, source IP/headers, protocol, zone, and route. Test with many independent connections and with keep-alive disabled only as a diagnostic. Fix readiness/endpoints, remove unintended stickiness, tune upstream max requests/connection or use request-aware balancing, and preserve intentional affinity only when the state model requires it.`},{question:"One pod uses much more CPU than other replicas. How do you find the cause?",answer:`Start by comparing how requests are distributed across pods. Check whether that pod owns a specific partition or shard of work, runs scheduled jobs, is doing a cache warm-up, is stuck retrying something, or is hitting its CPU limit and being throttled.

Capture a profile or thread dump from the busy pod, and line up its traces and logs by route or key against the other pods. That lets you confirm whether the extra load comes from uneven traffic, or because that pod is genuinely doing unique work the others aren't.`}]}]}]},s=t;export{s as default};
